{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532744","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532744"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:29:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:29:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14704"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14704","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14704"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.64,0.09,0.06,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7397"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58099"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7397","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7397"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14704"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43558"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"3636"},{"type":"tags","id":"3641"},{"type":"tags","id":"3799"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18039"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58099","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58099"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher is reviewing historical data from the 2014-2016 West African Ebola outbreak. She is designing a retrospective cohort study looking at the incidence of complications related to the Ebola virus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a characteristic manifestation of Ebola virus disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome","Haemorrhagic fever","Subacute sclerosing panencephalitis","Post-viral myocarditis","Acute disseminated encephalomyelitis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the clinical manifestations of Ebola virus disease is crucial for early recognition and management. The disease typically progresses through distinct phases, with potential progression to hemorrhagic manifestations in severe cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemorrhagic fever\u003C/strong\u003E is a characteristic manifestation of severe Ebola virus disease, though it occurs in less than 50% of cases. When present, it typically manifests after day 5 of illness and can include bleeding from mucosal surfaces, petechiae, ecchymoses, and oozing from venepuncture sites.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGuillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is an acute inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy that can occur following Zika virus infection but is not typically associated with Ebola virus disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubacute sclerosing panencephalitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare but fatal complication of measles virus infection that typically occurs years after the initial infection. It is not associated with Ebola virus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPost-viral myocarditis\u003C/strong\u003E is a known complication of various viral infections, particularly coxsackievirus and other enteroviruses, but is not a characteristic feature of Ebola virus disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute disseminated encephalomyelitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a post-infectious demyelinating disorder that can occur following various viral infections but is not characteristically associated with Ebola virus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe progression of Ebola typically follows a pattern: early non-specific symptoms (days 1-3), followed by gastrointestinal symptoms (days 3-5), then potentially hemorrhagic manifestations (after day 5). Understanding this progression is important for healthcare workers in endemic areas.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Haemorrhagic manifestations are a hallmark feature of severe Ebola virus disease, though they occur in less than half of cases.","Early symptoms of Ebola virus disease are non-specific and include fever, fatigue, myalgia, and headache.","The progression from early symptoms to haemorrhagic manifestations follows a predictable timeline in Ebola virus disease."],"references":["Jacob ST, Crozier I, Fischer WA 2nd, et al. Ebola virus disease. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2020;6(1):13. Published 2020 Feb 20. doi:10.1038/s41572-020-0147-3","Malvy D, McElroy AK, de Clerck H, G\u00fcnther S, van Griensven J. Ebola virus disease [published correction appears in Lancet. 2019 May 18;393(10185):2038. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(19)30960-2]. Lancet. 2019;393(10174):936-948. doi:10.1016/S0140-6736(18)33132-5"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43558"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14704"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43558","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43558"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-29T07:07:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-29T07:08:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7397"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58099"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"p